x: 100, // limit each IP to 100 requests per windowMs }); app.use(limiter); ``` 5. Use `csurf` for protection against Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks: ```javascript const csurf = require(\'csurf\'); app.use(csurf()); ``` 6. Update any dependencies regularly to ensure you’re using the most secure and up-to-date versions. You can use `npm audit` to check for known vulnerabilities. 7. Validate and sanitize user input to prevent injection attacks. Use libraries like `express-validator` or `joi` to help with input validation, and `sanitizer` or `dompurify` to sanitize input. 8. Implement proper error handling that doesn\'t expose stack traces or other sensitive information to the users. 9. Ensure that your application properly checks for user permissions before allowing access to sensitive actions or data. 10. Use secure cookies for storing the session ID by setting the `httpOnly` and `secure` options: ```javascript app.use(session({ secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET, resave: true, saveUninitialized: true, cookie: { httpOnly: true, secure: true } })); ``` 11. Set up HTTPS protocol with a TLS certificate to encrypt data in transit between the client and the server. 12. Regularly audit your codebase for security issues, possibly with automated tools or by hiring security professionals. 13. Consider using a Content Security Policy (CSP) to mitigate XSS risks by setting the appropriate HTTP headers. 14. Always keep the Node.js runtime and any dependencies up to date with the latest security patches. By implementing these changes, you can make your codebase more secure and resilient to common web vulnerabilities. This list is not exhaustive and security practices should be continually reviewed and enhanced."},{"prompt":"I want you to start answering the question by writing at least a 1000-word introduction to the question. After the introduction, I would like you to create a detailed listing containing the steps in your Answer. After the summary table, I want you t